sentence: Home Depot ( HD ) is expected to report its first-quarter numbers before the market open May 15, with analysts forecasting earnings of $2.07 per share.
The home goods retailer earned $1.67 during the same period last year, and the stock has remained relatively flat on the year, with shares up a modest 1.0% in 2018.
HD was recently trading at $189.95, down $17.65 from its 12-month high and $45.70 above its 12-month low.
Overall technical indicators for HD are bullish with a weak upward trend.
The stock has recent support above $185.00, and recent resistance below $190.50.
Of the 27 analysts who cover the stock, 19 rate it a "strong buy", three rate it a "buy", and five rate it a "hold".
HD gets a score of 73 from InvestorsObserver's Stock Score Report.
Home Depot enjoyed a multi-year bullish run on the back of a strong housing market, but shares have cooled off in 2018, with the stock rising a mere 1.0% year to date.

HD sold off in February in sympathy to a weak overall market, but as market conditions have improved in recent weeks the stock has managed to erase a significant amount of its February losses, and should continue to trend higher as long as its quarterly numbers are OK and the overall stock market does not encounter another sell off.
HD last reported earnings in late February, with results topping estimates on both the top and bottom line.
The street expects another earnings beat this quarter, with a whisper number of $2.11 for the quarter, slightly above the $2.07 consensus.

The housing market remains solid, and while interest rates have started to inch higher it will take a couple more rate hikes before rates hit a point that will start to have a material impact on home sales and prices.

Home Depot has posted better than expected earnings and sales for six straight quarters, and if it can extend that streak the stock should continue to build on recent gains and approach its all-time high it set in January before the overall market corrected.
HD trades at $189.95, with a $208.95 average price target.
If you want a bullish hedged trade on the stock, consider a June 165/170 bull-put credit spread for a 25-cent credit.
That's a potential 5.3% return (54.9% annualized*) and the stock would have to fall 10.4% to cause a problem.
If you want to take a bearish stance on the stock at this time, consider a July 210/220 bear-call credit spread for a $0.55 credit.
That's a potential 5.8% return (30.5% annualized*) and the stock would have to rise 10.8% to cause a problem.
